We had a great experience at taco daddy this past weekend. First of all, the ambiance was fun, lively and inviting. The service was great too. Despite not taking reservations they were very accommodating and helpful in getting our party of 12 seated and our waiter was very attentive and on point. The food and drinks were served quickly despite it being very crowded. I very much enjoyed my margarita and the selection of drink options. And last but not least the food was quite good. I got the tacos à la carte. The Carnitas and al Pastor were really good. The only small complaint was the shrimp taco wasn’t my favorite.  Not bad just nothing special. It mostly tasted like just shrimp and cheese and not much else. I would have added a mango coleslaw and cilantro or something. But other than that everything was great and we had a really good time! Overall great experience!

I am just catching up with reviews from my two week stay in Frederick around last Christmas. Unfortunately Taco Daddy was the worst of the restaurants I visited during my trip. The food was poor and the drinks were strong but flavorless. I see that TD likes to follow up on these reviews and ask "give us another try", but unfortunately unless this place completely overhauled everything, both from the kitchen and from the bar, there is nothing that could get me back there.

I made reservations on their website for Friday (last night) that took the number of people which was 6 of us( and 2 out of them drove from West Virginia and Gaithersburg for the special occasion to celebrate promotions and awards) at 6pm for reservations at 830pm. There is only options of 6:30 7:40 and 8:30 for the evening. I choose 830 put in my telephone number and the website said thank you for your request it's been sent. Thought it was odd I didn't get a confirmation. But I still went early at 815pm it was not that busy had a younger female at the desk and explained I made reservations but I was early. She gave me a weird look and said no we don't take reservations. I answered what do you mean you don't take reservations? I filled out the reservation online and it even took my telephone number. She answered back with we don't take reservations on the weekends. Of course I answered back with weekends are Saturday and Sunday's today is Friday and your website took the reservation along with my telephone number and said it has been sent in for the request. She went to go talk to the manager who I saw the gentleman with black hair short with his button down colored blue shirt speaking to her and waving his hands in the air. He never bothered to come out to my friends and I to even apologize or acknowledge the situation. Great management skills and customer service skills right??! The employee walk back and again said the same thing that there was nothing she could do they don't take reservations on the weekend and that if I wanted to wait they would try to find a table for me. Of course I was appalled by this point because I felt the customer service was downright terrible. I train people on customer service and it's a huge thing with the business where I work for and this place definitely needs those skills and the manager on duty totally disappointed me.  I don't know who trained him on his skills but he definitely needs a refresher. This business needs to know they need to acknowledge their faults because no business is perfect a simple apology goes a long way in the world of customer service especially in a food retail place that is geared by customers buying and purchasing things. If Taco Daddy ever needs some customer service training I'll be happy to lend a helping hand in that area because it's clear they need it. I will never return or give a second chance to this facility.

Okay, at best. It advertises itself as a cantina and taco bar. Atmosphere is decidedly low-rent college/sports bar with nary a nod to the origin of its food. Prices reflect the rent of the neighborhood,  not the value/quality of its food or atmosphere. Food... Ceviche : No, just NO. Whoever came up with this recipe has never, ever, actually tasted a real ceviche. Ours went back to the kitchen after two bites. Wrong variety of limes, in fact I'd be willing to bet the lime juice came out of a bottle. No other flavors present. Save yourself time and take a swig of the old squeeze bottle of lime juice in the back of your fridge. Guacamole : Lots of avocado and no mayo, good. Few, if any, other spices or ingredients, bad. Needs work. Fajitas: Average. Onions and green bell peppers only, light on the meats. Pricy for the quantity and quality. Drinks: Piña colada out of an artificially flavored mix bottle. Topped with whipped cream? Gross. White wine sangria made with low quality wine, also unpalatable. Bills itself as a neighborhood hangout, but prices are too high for that, and the food is not good enough to make up for it. I didn't go for the Tequila tasting, as more than two makes it impossible to tell the difference.

First I want to apologize for not taking the picture until I was already a taco in to the plate, as well as almost polishing off the sides of rice and beans. But I can’t even explain how excited I was when this came out. I ordered the Al Pastor taco plate for lunch. Hot and fresh, the first thing I noticed was the aroma of spices that came with the plate, perfectly arranged for presentation. The condiments were bursting with flavor, but not so much as to cover up the deliciousness of the meat itself. I opted to not squeeze fresh lime and add salsa so I could truly give an unadulterated review of the taco alone. Oh. My. Goodness! The meat was a perfect balance of juicy and crispy in texture, and the perfectly seasoned meat ensured that every bite was consistent in flavor throughout. The double layer of corn tortillas, the only tortillas that should accompany Al Pastor Tacos, could barely stand up to the amount of meat they packed into each taco. The second I tried with the Salsa Verde and lime. Equally as delicious with the added depth and heat one would hope from that added combination. The best surprise was that they didn’t overlook flavor when it came time to the arroz y frijoles. Perfect texture and expertly seasoned as well truly let me know that they weren’t just added as fillers for the plate, but truly were quality sides to make a rounded meal. The staff were all very friendly and never allowed my drink to remain empty without at least offering to refill it. Will definitely be coming back. Best of Frederick got it wrong this year.

I usually hate to write bad reviews, but I feel like I should warn other people of my experience there. Doesn't mean you shouldn't try it, but this is my opinion.  Firstly I ordered the nachos off of the menu and my wife ordered steak. After a 45-minute wait we got our nachos that seem to just be grated cheese covering flimsy tortilla chips with a dollop of sour cream and the rest of the fixings. It seemed to me that I could have gotten the same quality of nachoes if I microwaved homemade nachos and compared it to this places. It got to me lukewarm and that would be my only dig on this dish.  My wife ordered steak, I forgot if it was the fajitas or something else but it was steak nonetheless, and it came mostly cooked. But to be honest it had the quality of boiled meat, which doesn't sound great but I don't know how else to describe it. The flavor wasn't there, and  the reason why I am posting is because the bill was $30 plus and I feel like I could have gotten better quality somewhere else for less.  the staff here was really friendly and welcoming and made sure my drink was always topped off and that I had everything I needed! Thank you guys for the good customer service.  Just needs improvement on the food, which doesn't reflect the bartenders or waiters.
